        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/lehu/{size}/995_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-06-21T19:59:07.368Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Currently our FDB cluster has 70 storage nodes (K8s pods). We want to add 10 more to it. Our replication factor is 3, using FDB <strong>v6.2.27</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Is it better to add 10 pods at once or add in smaller batches (like 5+5, or 3+3+4)?</strong></p>\n<p>My main goal here is to minimize the temporary increase of disk usage during the rebalance.  I don\u2019t know how much (in terms of percentage) the rebalance would hike the disk usage. Is there a formula for a rough estimate?</p>\n<p>In the past we had some unpleasant experience with the temp disk space spike,  Last year with FDB <strong>v6.2.11</strong> we had a trouble (<a href=\"https://forums.foundationdb.org/t/newly-added-storage-nodes-have-disk-usage-at-98/2291\" class=\"inline-onebox\">Newly added storage nodes have disk usage at 98%</a>). We upgraded to v6.2.27. It has worked better.</p>\n<p>Last week our OS maintenance made several storage pods dropped out of the fdb cluster due to network security issue. Then I saw the disk usage in some pods go up to 90% during the rebalance. We know when disk usage reached 95%, the fdb cluster will be halted.</p>\n<p>Therefore we\u2019d like to be very cautious this time. Thanks.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 3,
        "updated_at": "2021-06-21T19:59:07.368Z",
